  abstract = {Reigning measures of psychological well-being have little theoretical grounding, despite an extensive\textbackslash nliterature on the contours of positive functioning. Aspects of well-being derived from this literature\textbackslash n(i.e., self-acceptance, positive relations with others, autonomy, environmental mastery, purpose in\textbackslash nlife, and personal growth) were operationalized. Three hundred and twenty-one men and women,\textbackslash ndivided among young, middle-aged, and older adults, rated themselves on these measures along with\textbackslash nsix instruments prominent in earlier studies (i.e., affect balance, life satisfaction, self-esteem, morale,\textbackslash nlocus of control, depression). Results revealed that positive relations with others, autonomy, purpose\textbackslash nin life, and personal growth were not strongly tied to prior assessment indexes, thereby supporting\textbackslash nthe claim that key aspects of positive functioning have not been represented in the empirical arena.\textbackslash nFurthermore, age profiles revealed a more differentiated pattern of well-being than is evident in prior\textbackslash nresearch.}
